            <section>
                <h2>Floats And Displays</h2>
                <p>We can use "Floats and Displays" to take up space in different ways in the page.</p>
                <p>An inline element will have items displayed horizontally and "inline" to other elements.</p>
                Like this: <span>Item1</span><span>Item2</span>
                <h3>Block vs Inline</h3>
                <p>display: block; makes an element take up the full width available, force a line break after it, and allows you to set its width and height.

display: inline; makes an element take up only the width it needs (based on its content), does not force a line break after it, and you cannot set its width or height. It only affects how the specific element behaves.
            </section>
        </article>
        <hr>
        <article>
            <section>
                <h2>Position-Static, Relative, Absolute, Fixed</h2>
                <p>I am guessing static positioning is the same as relative positioning; unchanged until it is moved.</p>
                <p style="position:relative; top:20px right: 40px">Relative positioning is normal positioning but can be moved by top, right, bottom , and left certain pixels assigned to it.</p>
                <p style="absolute; top: 100px; background-color: red;">Absolute positions itself from the ancestor element.</p>
                <p style="position: fixed; background-color: blue 20px;">Fixed positioning</p>
            </section>
